snippet.textDisplay: I can’t believe the amount of misinformation In this video. First off, store bought hotdogs are already cooked.  There might be some little specialty store somewhere that sells a raw hotdog but I’ve never seen one that does.  So you don’t actually cook a hotdog, you just choose the method you want to use to heat it up. The “expert” stated that Brats are already cooked.  That is incorrect. You can buy them already cooked or you can buy them raw.  Johnsonville as well as other brands make them both ways.  The expert stated that putting the hotdogs on an indoor electric grill gave them a smoky flavor. An indoor electric grill cannot give anything a true smoky flavor.  If you want a real smoky flavor you’ve got to use a grill with charcoal or wood. If Emily was after the easiest and quickest method why didn’t she just put the hotdog in a microwave for 30 seconds.  She complained about having to wait 15 seconds to steam her bun but said nothing about waiting for the water to boil or the 4-5 minutes she left her hotdog in the boiling water.  Again the hotdog is already cooked, it doesn’t take five minutes in boiling water to heat it up. Emily could have used a microwave instead and eaten her hotdog In less time than it took her to boil the water. The expert stated that bacon bits are not real bacon. Again that is incorrect. You can buy real bacon bits Or you can buy the fake little crunchy bacon bits. You can also buy real bacon pieces which are larger and much tastier than bacon bits.  These weren’t the only errors, just the ones I can easily recall. I am not any kind of expert yet I seem to know more than the experts.  Perhaps the expert ,was educated beyond her intelligence.

snippet.textDisplay: We make our level 3 hot dog from scratch. Once you've colonized your own planet, introduce the red onion crop and while those grow, invent the lamb. Now once you've discovered New France, you'll want some of their bread so now's a good time to invade their country and confiscate one of their thinner baguettes. Discover the tomato. Dehydrate it and make a paste to which you will add a bit of Middle Eastern and North African influence (if your new planet hasn't got a New Africa yet, now is a good time to allocate that while your lamb links are marinating in their own intestines) .
